26  Opinion of the Court  22-11707 
basis review and need only โbe rationally related to a legitimate 
governmental interest.โ  Jones v. Governor of Florida, 950 F.3d 795, 
809 (11th Cir. 2020).  Although not โtoothless,โ rational basis re-
view is โhighly deferential to government action.โ  Id. (quoting 
Schweiker v. Wilson, 450 U.S. 221, 234 (1981)). 
In other words, every time a court recognizes an asserted 
right as a fundamental right protected by the Constitution, the 
court, โto a great extent, place[s] the matter outside the arena of 
public debate and legislative action.โ Washington v. Glucksberg, 521 
U.S. 702, 720 (1997).  For that reason, the Supreme Court has in-
structed courts addressing substantive due process claims to โen-
gage[] in a careful analysis of the history of the right at issueโ and 
be โโreluctantโ to recognize rights that are not mentioned in the 
Constitution.โ  Dobbs, 142 S. Ct. at 2246โ47 (quoting Collins v. 
Harker Heights, 503 U.S. 115, 125 (1992)). 
