B.  Equal Protection 

UUSSCCAA1111  CCaassee::  2222--1111770077          DDooccuummeenntt::  112259- 1       D  aDtaet eF iFleilde:d 0: 90/81/12/12/022032 3       P  aPgaeg:e 8: 03 8o fo 1f 0519  
38  Opinion of the Court  22-11707 
The Equal Protection Clause provides that no state shall 
โdeny to any person within its jurisdiction the equal protection of 
the laws.โ  U.S. Const. amend. XIV, ยง 1.  The Equal Protection 
Clause is โessentially a direction that all persons similarly situated 
should be treated alike,โ City of Cleburne v. Cleburne Living Ctr., 473 
U.S. 432, 439 (1985), and โsimply keeps governmental decisionmak-
ers from treating differently persons who are in all relevant respects 
alike,โ Nordlinger v. Hahn, 505 U.S. 1, 10 (1992). 
โIn considering whether state legislation violates the Equal 
Protection Clause . . . we apply different levels of scrutiny to differ-
ent types of classifications.โ  Clark v. Jeter, 486 U.S. 456, 461 (1988).  
All statutory classifications must, at a minimum, satisfy rational ba-
sis review.  Id.  Classifications based on race or national origin, 
however, are reviewed under the โmost exactingโ level of scrutiny: 
strict scrutiny.  Id.  Between rational basis review and strict scrutiny 
lies โa level of intermediate scrutiny,โ which applies to classifica-
tions based on sex or illegitimacy.  Id. 
Thus, a government policy that distinguishes on the basis of 
sex is permissible under the Equal Protection Clause โonly if it sat-
isfies intermediate scrutiny.โ  Adams ex rel. Kasper v. Sch. Bd. of St. 
Johns Cnty., 57 F.4th 791, 801 (11th Cir. 2022).  Under that standard, 
the party seeking to uphold the policy carries the burden of โshow-
ing that the [sex-based] classification serves โimportant governmen-
tal objectives and that the discriminatory means employedโ are 
โsubstantially  related  to  the  achievement  of  those  objectives.โโ  

