Skrmetti, 73 F.4th at 419 (finding it โhighly unlikelyโ that the plain-
tiffs could show that Tennesseeโs substantially similar law โlacks a 
rational basisโ).  Because the district court erroneously departed 
from that standard, its assessment regarding the Minor Plaintiffsโ 
likelihood of success as to their equal protection claim cannot sup-
port the preliminary injunction.  We reason as follows. 
To  begin,  we  reject  the  view  that  section  4(a)(1)โ(3) 
amounts to a sex-based classification subject to intermediate scru-
tiny.  As mentioned, one of the Minor Plaintiffsโ arguments is that 
section 4(a)(1)โ(3) directly classifies on the basis of sex because it 
โuses explicitly sex-based terms to criminalize certain treatments 
based on a minorโs โsex.โโ  Of course, section 4(a)(1)โ(3) discusses 
sex insofar as it generally addresses treatment for discordance be-
tween biological sex and gender identity, and insofar as it identifies 
the applicable cross-sex hormone(s) for each sexโestrogen for 
males and testosterone and other androgens for females.  We 

