BRASHER, Circuit Judge, concurring: 
I concur in the Courtโs opinion. I write separately to focus 
on the plainti๏ฌsโ equal protection claim.  
The resolution of an equal protection claim often turns on 
the level of scrutiny that we applyโrational basis, intermediate, or 
strict. The plainti๏ฌs argue that the statute classi๏ฌes based on sex, 
which warrants intermediate scrutiny. The Court rejects that argu-
ment, and, after much deliberation and research, I agree. Ala-
bamaโs statute does not treat one sex di๏ฌerently than the other. It 
does not use sex as a proxy for some more germane classi๏ฌcation. 
And it is not based on a sex stereotype. Instead, I think the law is 
best read to classifyโnot based on sexโbut as between minors 
who want puberty blockers and hormones to treat โa discordance 
between [their] sex and sense of gender identity,โ Ala. Code ยง 26-
26-2(2), and those minors who want these drugs to treat a di๏ฌerent 
condition.  
But even if the statute did discriminate based on sex, I think 
it is likely to satisfy intermediate scrutiny. If Alabamaโs statute in-
volves a sex-based classi๏ฌcation that triggers heightened scrutiny, it 
does so because it is otherwise impossible to regulate these drugs 
di๏ฌerently when they are prescribed as a treatment for gender dys-
phoria than when they are prescribed for other purposes. As long 
as the state has a substantial justi๏ฌcation for regulating di๏ฌerently 
the use of puberty blockers and hormones for di๏ฌerent purposes, 
then I think this law satis๏ฌes intermediate scrutiny. 


